         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">10/8/70 ¶  ¶ I just received the copy of your excellent students flora, dear Dr Hooker. ¶  I like the  ¶ plan ¶  of the work much. It comes very much in detail near Kochs Taschenbuch der deutsche Flor...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">70.08.10a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 442.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">10/8/70</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I just received the copy of your excellent students flora, dear Dr Hooker.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1870).</p>
               </note> I like the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">plan</hi>
               </seg> of the work much. It comes very much in detail near Kochs Taschenbuch der deutsche Flora<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">W. Koch (1844).</p>
               </note> and revived my reminiscenses of field searches 30 years ago with great vivacity. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Prof Olivers last edition of the Kew Guide<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Oliver (1870).</p>
               </note> pleases me also, but I missed (perhaps overlooked?) measurements of the gigantic Eucalypts and a few other striking notes, such as [our] <name key="Todea">Todea</name>.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Oliver quotes, on pp. 94-5, part of B67.13.02 concerning the size of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>
                     </seg>; and on p. 96 quotes M on the tree fern <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Dicksonia antarctica.</seg> No special mention is made of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Todea">Todea</name>
                     </seg>. For an analysis of M’s claims for tall trees, see Mace (1996).</p>
               </note> Perhaps the Professor never had my Exhibition reports<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The text ends without valediction near the bottom of the back page of the folio.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Todea">Todea</name>
            </p>
